1039e65dae62b8a1991f6a1cf24fbb60b50a7ba75d731a8f47d2a0b284b1fa67,brooke2017,sea_level_indicator,5.1. Past sea levels and shorelines,narrative_fallback_1,,,inferred_map,,-35.0,MSL,reported,submerged_beach,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-37.5, -32.5]","""Holocene""",stratigraphic_context,"submerged beach at 5.1. Past sea levels and shorelines, reported around 35 m depth",5.1. Past sea levels and shorelines,"Palaeoshorelines on the Australian continental shelf: Morphology, sea-level relationship and applications to environmental management and archaeology",https://doi.org/10.1016/j.csr.2016.12.012,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""5.1. Past sea levels and shorelines"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""The more frequent sea-level stands broadly match the depth ranges of palaeoshorelines that have been mapped on the Australian continental shelf (Fig. 3). Given the stability of the shelf, its wide range of oceanographic regimes and high potential to preserve drowned structures, the results are useful as a global indicator of the depth zones in which shoreline structures were well-developed during the Late Quaternary. The sea-level modes identified indicate the range of depths in which palaeoshorelines, if preserved, are likely to occur on other shelves. For example, early Holocene coral reefs sit in depths of around 30\u201340 m at many locations on th""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 35.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": ""Holocene"", ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-35,-35,-35,-35
0806da0cc9aa9a48471403f5ecbe61d75f5391c662da5666d50a39724ae53103,brooke2017,sea_level_indicator,5.3. Coral reefs,narrative_fallback_2,,,inferred_map,,-45.0,MSL,reported,marine_terrace,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-47.5, -42.5]",25.0,stratigraphic_context,"marine terrace at 5.3. Coral reefs, reported around 45 m depth",5.3. Coral reefs,"Palaeoshorelines on the Australian continental shelf: Morphology, sea-level relationship and applications to environmental management and archaeology",https://doi.org/10.1016/j.csr.2016.12.012,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""5.3. Coral reefs"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""On the shelf edge seawards of the Great Barrier Reef (GBR), a series of coast-parallel banks and terraces are drowned reefs that last grew when sea level was tens of metres lower than present, and align with a number of sea-level modes (Table 1; Fig. 4e). Extensive carbonate banks on the middle to outer shelf, at a depth of approximately 27 m, appear to represent drowned coral reefs (Harris et al., 2013; Abbey et al., 2011). On the GBR shelf edge, terraces also occur at depths of approximately 40\u201350 m, 80\u201390 m and between 100 and 120 m (Beaman et al., 2008; Yokoyama et al., 2011), and record phases of reef growth that occurred from shortly before the Last Glacial Maxim""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 45.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": 25.0, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-45,-45,-45,-45
49ed43192287759a97df7ea52d1df814751072bc03a38a5335a2a5c89c73bd45,brooke2017,sea_level_indicator,5.5. Erosional features,narrative_fallback_4,,,inferred_map,,-84.0,MSL,reported,submerged_beach,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-86.5, -81.5]",21.0,stratigraphic_context,"submerged beach at 5.5. Erosional features, reported around 84 m depth",5.5. Erosional features,"Palaeoshorelines on the Australian continental shelf: Morphology, sea-level relationship and applications to environmental management and archaeology",https://doi.org/10.1016/j.csr.2016.12.012,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""5.5. Erosional features"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Evidence for erosion is observed across a range of modal depths on the Australian shelf, indicating repeated episodes of shoreline sculpturing during the Late Quaternary. Thus, benches cut into the seabed on the Rottnest and Lord Howe Island shelves occur at around the 70 m isobath (Brooke et al., 2010a, b). However, on the Lord Howe Island Shelf, there is a series of benches between 65 and 100 m depth (Woodroffe et al., 2010) that likely relate to interstadial periods of lower sea level, possibly in MIS 3. On the Northwest Shelf, a submarine cliff with up to 8 m of relief occurs in segments along hundreds of kilometres of shelf, approximately parallel to the modern coast, at a depth of aroun""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 84.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": 21.0, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-84,-84,-84,-84
570e3082ccf12c6ea5b2696cd399083d3ec69b3665cd4db2e8d5e1de685be5ce,brooke2017,sea_level_indicator,5.7. Examples from other shelves,narrative_fallback_6,,,inferred_map,,-37.0,MSL,reported,marine_terrace,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-39.5, -34.5]","""LGM""",stratigraphic_context,"marine terrace at 5.7. Examples from other shelves, reported around 37 m depth",5.7. Examples from other shelves,"Palaeoshorelines on the Australian continental shelf: Morphology, sea-level relationship and applications to environmental management and archaeology",https://doi.org/10.1016/j.csr.2016.12.012,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""5.7. Examples from other shelves"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Wave-cut terraces and cliffs formed during lower sea levels have also been mapped on the South African shelf (Cawthra et al., 2014, 2015) and in detail at several sites on shelves around the Iberian Peninsula and the Balearic Islands (Fern\u00e1ndez-Salas et al., 2015). These include a series of terraces on the Cantabrian Shelf at depths of 37 m, 52\u201356 m, 70\u201375 m and 87\u201390 m (Galparsoro et al., 2010); several terraces between 50 and 84 m on the Gulf of Cadiz Shelf; and terraces on the middle and outer areas of the southeastern and Balearic shelves (Fern\u00e1ndez-Salas et al., 2015). In all c""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 37.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": ""LGM"", ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-37,-37,-37,-37
