4994e7a29279cb795c53012e55ff4334375dad31045a5f9044a475b796515d50,cawthra2015,sea_level_indicator,Mossel Bay continental shelf,mineru_feature_table_1,-34.1832022,22.1536248,inferred_text,5000.0,-45.0,MSL,reported,marine_terrace,MinerU interpreted feature table; facies=N/A,"[-45.0, -45.0]",null,stratigraphic_context,Terrace at 45 m BMSL: 2.7–0.07 Ma (derived from sea-level records of Lisiecki & Raymo 2005; Bintanja & van de Wal 2008),"Mossel Bay, Garden Route District Municipality, Western Cape, 6500, South Africa","Submerged shorelines and landscape features offshore of Mossel Bay, South Africa",https://doi.org/10.1144/SP411.11,0.8,"Extracted from MinerU interpreted geomorphic feature table. Geocoded from contextual query 'Mossel Bay, South Africa'.","{""page"": ""11"", ""figure"": null, ""table"": ""Table 2. Interpreted timing for the formation of the geomorphic features documented on the Mossel Bay continental shelf"", ""section"": null, ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Terrace at 45 m BMSL | N/A | 2.7\u20130.07 Ma (derived from sea-level records of Lisiecki & Raymo 2005; Bintanja & van de Wal 2008)""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 45.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Age context inferred from table/text when present.""}]",-45,-45,-45,-45
7cd78037f90532f0ad06d314634989de60dba5be44d78a463ec61e36bfedb510,cawthra2015,sea_level_indicator,Mossel Bay continental shelf,mineru_feature_text_1,-34.1832022,22.1536248,inferred_text,5000.0,-45.0,MSL,reported,marine_terrace,MinerU text feature paragraph,"[-45.0, -45.0]",null,stratigraphic_context,Terraces,"Mossel Bay, Garden Route District Municipality, Western Cape, 6500, South Africa","Submerged shorelines and landscape features offshore of Mossel Bay, South Africa",https://doi.org/10.1144/SP411.11,0.8,"Extracted from MinerU Markdown feature paragraph. Geocoded from contextual query 'Mossel Bay, South Africa'.","{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""Terraces"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Terraces. Along the south coast, the 245 m isobath separates the inner shelf from the mid-shelf (Fig. 2). This bathymetric zone is distinct and forms a shelf terrace, or break in the dominant gradient. Heap & Harris (2008) defined terraces as relatively flat areas of regional extent, bordered by steeper margins. The marked change in gradient at this depth has been described by Martin & Flemming (1987) as one of four prominent south coast nickpoints (at water depths of 105\u2013100, 80\u201375, 55\u2013 50 and c. 40 m).""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 45.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Age context inferred from table/text when present.""}]",-45,-45,-45,-45
1f3fc47084d3da18bc96fe7f569e476bbc7f34d87eb052522442216b049a3987,cawthra2015,sea_level_indicator,Mossel Bay continental shelf,mineru_feature_text_2,-34.1832022,22.1536248,inferred_text,5000.0,-23.0,MSL,reported,wave_cut_notch_or_bench,MinerU text feature paragraph,"[-23.0, -23.0]",null,stratigraphic_context,Sea cliffs,"Mossel Bay, Garden Route District Municipality, Western Cape, 6500, South Africa","Submerged shorelines and landscape features offshore of Mossel Bay, South Africa",https://doi.org/10.1144/SP411.11,0.8,"Extracted from MinerU Markdown feature paragraph. Geocoded from contextual query 'Mossel Bay, South Africa'.","{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""Sea cliffs"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Sea cliffs. Offshore of Cape St Blaize, the hardrock geological substrate that characterizes the Pinnacle Point coastline extends offshore for 1.5 km towards the east (Fig. 4). From the base at 23 m bmsl the submerged seacliffs rise 20 m off the seabed and this outcrop correlates to Acoustic Facies a on the side-scan sonar record (Table 1). The seawards margin of the outcrop is defined by incised caves and overhangs, and is eroded into an embayment comparable in size and form to the presently exposed coastal cliffs at Pinnacle Point and Cape St Blaize. These submerged seacliffs are therefore a lowstand expression of a continuous coastal promontory.""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 23.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Age context inferred from table/text when present.""}]",-23,-23,-23,-23
48bf1689ad08c6d33cfce2bdf1e417953cbd3e6318f4f369cb3068e07d858857,cawthra2015,sea_level_indicator,Mossel Bay continental shelf,mineru_feature_text_3,-34.1832022,22.1536248,inferred_text,5000.0,-45.0,MSL,reported,submerged_beach,MinerU text feature paragraph,"[-55.0, -35.0]",null,stratigraphic_context,Shelf banks/shoals,"Mossel Bay, Garden Route District Municipality, Western Cape, 6500, South Africa","Submerged shorelines and landscape features offshore of Mossel Bay, South Africa",https://doi.org/10.1144/SP411.11,0.8,"Extracted from MinerU Markdown feature paragraph. Geocoded from contextual query 'Mossel Bay, South Africa'.","{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""Shelf banks/shoals"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Shelf banks/shoals. A shelf bank/shoal is considered to be an area of seabed characterized by widely spaced isobaths at the base, intercepted by areas of relief and incision (Heap & Harris 2008). Numerous ridges with prominent relief compared to the surrounding seabed lie in water depths of 35\u201355 m in the eastern side of the study area offshore the Groot Brak River (Fig. 5). The ridges are typically separated by depressions \u2013 hence, the classification as shoals \u2013 but in places they coalesce, bifurcate and they can be grouped into distinct clusters. The most significant linear features trend east\u2013west and individual ridges reach maximum widths of 400 m. In the study area, the shoals extend 6.5 km along-strike and continue eastwards beyond the extent of the mapped zone. These features are cl""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 45.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Age context inferred from table/text when present.""}]",-45,-45,-45,-45
