6cedc5b6cf840386b7507adb743ce4a59a6245fa1d9c2eac350b69a9a7cf7a56,foglini2015,sea_level_indicator,Sikka il-Bajda,narrative_fallback_8,,,inferred_map,,-95.0,MSL,reported,marine_terrace,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-97.5, -92.5]",null,other,"marine terrace at Sikka il-Bajda, reported around 95 m depth",Sikka il-Bajda,Late Quaternary coastal landscape morphology and evolution of the Maltese Islands (Mediterranean Sea) reconstructed from high-resolution seafloor data,https://doi.org/10.1144/SP411.12,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""Sikka il-Bajda"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Downslope of the escarpment, the seafloor is defined by flat terraces limited to landwards by concave breaks of slope. The latter have a similar orientation to the escarpment and occur at a depth of 108 m; they range from 5 to 12 km in length and from 800 to 1000 m in width. The sediment covering the area consists of fine silty sand with a clayey fraction. The enlargement of the platform and its increase in depth southwards is probably due to a change in lithology from the harder Lower Coralline Limestone to the softer Globigerina Limestone (Micallef et al. 2013). These marine terraces were probably formed by subaerial weathering and""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 95.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""other"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-95,-95,-95,-95
