c58e943038d1d489cef5c08b4914f61dc464e33d6ed6508eff738f045fa959c1,lebrec2022,sea_level_indicator,8.1. Age and preservation of MSLD shorelines,narrative_fallback_5,,,inferred_map,,-127.0,MSL,reported,submerged_beach,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-129.5, -124.5]","""LGM""",stratigraphic_context,"submerged beach at 8.1. Age and preservation of MSLD shorelines, reported around 127 m depth",8.1. Age and preservation of MSLD shorelines,Morphology and distribution of submerged palaeoshorelines: Insights from the North West Shelf of Australia,https://doi.org/10.1016/j.earscirev.2021.103864,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""8.1. Age and preservation of MSLD shorelines"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""This being said, a few comments can be made on the age and preservation of the Rowley Shelf MSLD shorelines. First, it should be noted that the LGM was identified at depths comprised between 121 and 125 m below sea level in the Bonaparte Basin (Sahul Shelf), further north along the NWS (Yokoyama et al., 2001a), which suggests that MSLD 125 could correspond to the LGM. This interpretation is further supported by age dating performed offshore Barrow Island, at IODP site U1461, that identified the LGM 14 m below the seabed, in water depth of 127 m (Ishiwa et al., 2019b), in line with the observation of MSLD 125 offshore Broome (Fig. 15D and B). Recent work on the Great Ba""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 127.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": ""LGM"", ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-127,-127,-127,-127
f16be55254fe581debf6dd575002794950fa6e746d1d4f850625e280e1311f6b,lebrec2022,sea_level_indicator,8.2. Influence of palaeoshorelines on shelf morphology,narrative_fallback_6,,,inferred_map,,-80.0,MSL,reported,marine_terrace,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-82.5, -77.5]",null,other,"marine terrace at 8.2. Influence of palaeoshorelines on shelf morphology, reported around 80 m depth",8.2. Influence of palaeoshorelines on shelf morphology,Morphology and distribution of submerged palaeoshorelines: Insights from the North West Shelf of Australia,https://doi.org/10.1016/j.earscirev.2021.103864,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""8.2. Influence of palaeoshorelines on shelf morphology"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""ccumulate on the outer shelf, leaving relict features outcropping on most of the seabed (James et al., 2004; Jones, 1971; Jones, 1973). Interestingly, no kilometre-scale relict bioconstructed reefs, including coral-reef terraces, were observed along the Rowley Shelf during this study. This is in stark contrasts to the eastward facing Great Barrier Reef, along which relict linear reefs several km-long were identified at water depths of 80 m, 90 m, 100 m and 110 m (Webster et al., 2018). Along the Rowley Shelf, kilometre-scale linear features seem to be systematically formed by relict coastal features, as no morphologies characteristic of true coral reefs $( \\boldsymbol { \\mathrm { e . } } \\boldsymbol { \\mathrm { g . } } ,$ atoll morphologies, spurs and grooves, reef pass; see Khanna et al.,""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 80.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""other"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-80,-80,-80,-80
