e300f7d8fa06906638311550e347523541ffe2e5fcfa7b793bda2712b3c371a5,bateman2011,sea_level_indicator,9.1. The Middle to Late Pleistocene evolution of the Wilderness embayment,narrative_fallback_1,-33.9932378,22.5786317,inferred_text,5000.0,-50.0,MSL,reported,marine_terrace,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-52.5, -47.5]",130.0,stratigraphic_context,"marine terrace at 9.1. The Middle to Late Pleistocene evolution of the Wilderness embayment, reported around 50 m depth","Wilderness, Garden Route District Municipality, Western Cape, 6560, South Africa","The evolution of coastal barrier systems: a case study of the Middle-Late Pleistocene Wilderness barriers, South Africa",https://doi.org/10.1016/j.quascirev.2010.10.003,0.95,"Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review. Geocoded from contextual query 'Wilderness, Western Cape, South Africa'.","{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""9.1. The Middle to Late Pleistocene evolution of the Wilderness embayment"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Evidence for higher sea levels is recognised throughout the Wilderness embayment. These include erosional \u201cterraces\u201d at various altitudes, e.g. the rock platform at w6e8 m amsl backed by a cliff the island in Eilandvlei, and exposures of marginal marine calcarenite typically ca 5e7 m above modern sea levels (Martin, 1962; Fig. 2f), e.g. at the base of the Seaward barrier to the east of Eilandvlei. Also, much of the seaward margin of the Middle barrier (e.g. between Sedgefield and the Goukamma River) has been oversteepened, forming a clear palaeo-sea cliff (Illenberger, 1996; Fig. 1b). This evidence indicates marine inundations of a significant portion of the embayment had taken""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 50.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": 130.0, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-50,-50,-50,-50
7dac8d7fb9640a1c46a7a386344db636eb26af882a66054492cf5125750c525d,firth1993,sea_level_indicator,Resolution Guyot,narrative_fallback_1,45.4204505,9.2598954,inferred_text,10000.0,-1500.0,MSL,reported,guyot_or_drowned_platform,narrative fallback: guyot or drowned carbonate platform,"[-1600.0, -1400.0]",null,other,"Guyot or drowned carbonate platform at Resolution Guyot, reported around 1500 m depth","Eos, Metanopoli, Triulzo Inferiore, Triulzo, San Donato Milanese, Milano, Lombardia, Italia",EOS,,0.8,"Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of a flat-topped seamount, guyot, or drowned carbonate platform. Summit/platform depth is treated as a broad sea-level indicator pending review for subsidence, erosion, and platform-growth history. Geocoded from contextual query 'EOS'.","{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""ODP Leg 143 Shipboard Scientific Party"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""The Western Pacific is strewn with chains and clusters of seamounts, many of which are now flat-topped submarine seamounts, or guyots, with summit depths of about 1500 m. Many guyots are capped by shallow-water carbonate platform sediments overlying volcanic substrate. Guyot sediments can serve as \""dip sticks\"" to monitor subsidence rates and relative changes in sea level for times when upward carbonate-platform growth occurred during tectonic subsidence of their foundations. Such sediments encode the timing and sense of sea-level rises and falls in their mineralogy, textures, and fossils. Guyot volcanic pedestals preserve, in their mineralogy and chemistry, clues to the nature of their parent mantl""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 1500.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""other"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-1500,-1500,-1500,-1500
d41b4df6d4011507482e5314ff179405f9bf5bfa515e6e9d002f6b04971c52ed,flood2001,sea_level_indicator,Hawaiian-Emperor chain,narrative_fallback_1,,,inferred_map,,-30.0,MSL,reported,guyot_or_drowned_platform,narrative fallback: guyot or drowned carbonate platform,"[-130.0, 70.0]",34000.0,stratigraphic_context,"Guyot or drowned carbonate platform at Hawaiian-Emperor chain, reported around 30 m depth",Hawaiian-Emperor chain,The \`Darwin Point' of Paci¢c Ocean atolls and guyots: a reappraisal,https://doi.org/10.1016/S0031-0182(01)00390-X,0.55,"Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of a flat-topped seamount, guyot, or drowned carbonate platform. Summit/platform depth is treated as a broad sea-level indicator pending review for subsidence, erosion, and platform-growth history.","{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""Abstract"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""w 30 m with respect to sea level and the rate of sea-level rise is more than 15 mm/yr, the atoll will drown. Results of the Ocean Drilling Program legs 143 and 144, which investigated the histories of several NW Pacific guyots, indicate that the demise of the shallow-water carbonate platforms there was related to either a temporal (110^100 Ma) eustatic sea-level event, the paleolatitude location (0^10\u00b3S) of nutrient-rich water, and/or increased seawater temperature (greenhouse effect) unconducive to the production of calcium carbonate by shallow-water organisms. Hence, the Darwin Point phenomena of atolls and guyots cannot be viewed as a manifestation of any single factor, rather, it results from a combination of factors including: decreased water temperature and light related to higher la""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 30.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": 34000.0, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-30,-30,-30,-30
