7fc43879271dcac5b2a964693cfa3c59d6f5dce50009aa9920b78cc57ef82a1e,vogt1984,sea_level_indicator,Geisha guyot chain,narrative_fallback_1,,,inferred_map,,-1647.0,MSL,reported,guyot_or_drowned_platform,narrative fallback: guyot or drowned carbonate platform,"[-1747.0, -1547.0]",null,other,"Guyot or drowned carbonate platform at Geisha guyot chain, reported around 1647 m depth",Geisha guyot chain,The Geisha Guyots: Multibeam Bathymetry and Morphometric Interpretation,https://doi.org/10.1029/JB089iB13p11085,0.55,"Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of a flat-topped seamount, guyot, or drowned carbonate platform. Summit/platform depth is treated as a broad sea-level indicator pending review for subsidence, erosion, and platform-growth history.","{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""SUMMIT PLATEAU BATHYMETRY"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Minimum summit depths along the Geisha guyots lie within a relatively narrow range, from 1647 m (Charlie Johnson) to 1318 m (Takuy\u014d-Daini). The minimum depths do not appear to vary significantly either along the 1000-km-long chain or as a function of plateau area. The mean summit depth for the eight guyots is $1418 \\pm 59$ m. This average does not differ significantly from a 1400-m average for the six guyots known to Heezen et al. [1973]. Depths reported there are within $\\pm 50$ m of the multibeam-derived values for Makarov, Isakov, Thomas Washington, Winterer, and Seiko (now Takuy\u014d-Daini); the only significant""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 1647.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""other"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-1647,-1647,-1647,-1647
18d62aade1bde0800e3631824667df565f23740aed23fa1148d7c8c8065f40d8,wilson1998,sea_level_indicator,Surviving atolls and platform erosion,narrative_fallback_1,,,inferred_map,,-1350.0,MSL,reported,guyot_or_drowned_platform,narrative fallback: guyot or drowned carbonate platform,"[-1450.0, -1250.0]",null,other,"Guyot or drowned carbonate platform at Surviving atolls and platform erosion, reported around 1350 m depth",Surviving atolls and platform erosion,The paradox of drowned carbonate platforms and the origin of Cretaceous Pacific guyots,,0.55,"Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of a flat-topped seamount, guyot, or drowned carbonate platform. Summit/platform depth is treated as a broad sea-level indicator pending review for subsidence, erosion, and platform-growth history.","{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""Surviving atolls and platform erosion"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""The possibility that the tops of the guyot shallow-water carbonate platforms may have been subjected to significant erosion cannot be discounted. Therefore, calculated ages and latitudes for platform drowning must be regarded as maximum estimates (oldest dates; highest latitudes). Nevertheless, five lines of evidence suggest that erosion-induced uncertainties in estimation of these ages and latitudes are relatively small and that our interpretation of these data is therefore robust: (1) The latitudinal range of the guyots today (,308, Fig. 1) is large in comparison to our estimated latitudinal range for platfo""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 1350.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""other"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material""