d1aff3d36c42749507471acf3f0f1ac3aca95bea75646cd04f5edcc3df5e4048,cerrone2021,sea_level_indicator,5.2. The buried paleoshorelines remnants in the southern mountain front of Mt. Fellino ridge: Marine terrace T2,narrative_fallback_1,,,inferred_map,,-115.0,MSL,reported,submerged_beach,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-117.5, -112.5]",null,other,"submerged beach at 5.2. The buried paleoshorelines remnants in the southern mountain front of Mt. Fellino ridge: Marine terrace T2, reported around 115 m depth",5.2. The buried paleoshorelines remnants in the southern mountain front of Mt. Fellino ridge: Marine terrace T2,Development and deformation of marine terraces: Constraints to the evolution of the Campania Plain Quaternary coastal basin (Italy),https://doi.org/10.1016/j.geomorph.2021.107725,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""5.2. The buried paleoshorelines remnants in the southern mountain front of Mt. Fellino ridge: Marine terrace T2"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Slightly different stratigraphic successions are associated with the abrasion platforms in the nearby Sites 5 and 3 (Fig. 2). The paleoshoreline T2 remnant outcropping in Site 5 (Fig. 5), well exposed in a N-S oriented quarry wall, consists of a horizontal wave-cut platform located at 115 m a.s.l. covered by about 3 m thick cross-bedded, moderately sorted, fine arenites (Sample 5a, Supplementary materials 2) that, in the inner part of the abrasion platform, pass laterally into a coarsegrained massive deposit (Fig. 5A).""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 115.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""other"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-115,-115,-115,-115
1027d4ef4b611721611a8ff6edc1042055f60ff1a84b23197d00c89d708e8ad8,cerrone2021,sea_level_indicator,5.2. The buried paleoshorelines remnants in the southern mountain front of Mt. Fellino ridge: Marine terrace T2,narrative_fallback_2,,,inferred_map,,-110.0,MSL,reported,submerged_beach,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-112.5, -107.5]",null,other,"submerged beach at 5.2. The buried paleoshorelines remnants in the southern mountain front of Mt. Fellino ridge: Marine terrace T2, reported around 110 m depth",5.2. The buried paleoshorelines remnants in the southern mountain front of Mt. Fellino ridge: Marine terrace T2,Development and deformation of marine terraces: Constraints to the evolution of the Campania Plain Quaternary coastal basin (Italy),https://doi.org/10.1016/j.geomorph.2021.107725,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""5.2. The buried paleoshorelines remnants in the southern mountain front of Mt. Fellino ridge: Marine terrace T2"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Intense quarrying activity has been carried out in the eastern part of Mt. Fellino ridge (Sites 6 and 7; Fig. 2), where only few outcrops of the raised paleoshorelines are available. Of those quarries, the huge one in Site 6 corresponds to one of the outcrops detected by Romano et al. (1994). There, an abrasion platform (Fig. 7A\u2013D), which cuts the limestone strata dipping at high angle towards the S-SE, is covered by a thin veneer of clast-supported, well-rounded carbonate pebble and cobble which pass upwards to a decimetre-thick layer of arenites with quartz grains (Fig. 7B\u2013C). The elevation of the abrasion platform inner edge is located at 110 m a.s.l. (Fig. 7).""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 110.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""other"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-110,-110,-110,-110
dd292d036e3ea836e95b32cefe2802ff88e94b5a07e3a1bfc81db626abed7c5f,chaytor2008,sea_level_indicator,"Bowen Point, Flatts, Hamilton, CR 01, Bermuda",page_12_feature_1,32.3331444,-64.7419439,inferred_text,5000.0,6.0,MSL,SRTM15+V2,submerged_beach,page OCR extracted from figure/table/map block,null,null,other,"Measuring vertical tectonic motion at the intersection of the Santa Cruz–Catalina Ridge and Northern Channel Islands platform, California Continental Borderland, using submerged paleoshorelines","Bowen Point, Flatts, Hamilton, CR 01, Bermuda","Measuring vertical tectonic motion at the intersection of the Santa Cruz–Catalina Ridge and Northern Channel Islands platform, California Continental Borderland, using submerged paleoshorelines",https://doi.org/10.1130/B26316.1,0.7,"Extracted from page OCR block on page 12 with cue 'Figure 7. (A) Close-up of the bathymetry, NCI-S1 paleoshoreline, and terrace features on the southern Northern Channel I' from source 'mineru_chart'. Place name geocoded from query 'Bowen Point'.","{""page"": ""12"", ""figure"": ""Figure 7. (A) Close-up of the bathymetry, NCI-S1 paleoshoreline, and terrace features on the southern Northern Channel I"", ""table"": null, ""section"": null, ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Figure 7. (A) Close-up of the bathymetry, NCI-S1 paleoshoreline, and terrace features on the southern Northern Channel Islands platform shelf edge between Santa Cruz and Anacapa Islands. The trace of the Santa Cruz Island fault (SCIF) is indicated as it crosses onto the platform, where it is likely related to destabilization of the slope. Inset: profi le A\u2013A\u2032, showing the morphology of the cliff-back LGM terrace, with approximate locations of the Santa Cruz Island fault and an additional fault indicated (fault movement indicated by x-away, o-toward). (B) Close-up of the bathymetry, NCI-S1 paleoshoreline, and terrace features on the southern Northern Channel Islands platform shelf edge near Bowen Point, south of Santa Cruz Island. Inset: profi le A\u2013A\u2032, showing the morphological slope breaks""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": null, ""reported_datum"": null, ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": 6.0, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": 6.0, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Elevation sampled from SRTM15+V2 at inferred coordinates because source elevation was not reported. Treat this as approximate spatial context, not a surveyed sample elevation.""}","[{""method"": ""other"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""No direct age model extracted from page OCR block.""}]",6,6,6,6
e55e834aba9c726d51fdec49a3560510f7157d32741503ac087d3dac4d5a1929,chaytor2008,sea_level_indicator,Eastern Northern Channel Islands Platform,narrative_fallback_1,,,inferred_map,,-95.0,MSL,reported,marine_terrace,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-97.5, -92.5]","""LGM""",stratigraphic_context,"marine terrace at Eastern Northern Channel Islands Platform, reported around 95 m depth",Eastern Northern Channel Islands Platform,"Measuring vertical tectonic motion at the intersection of the Santa Cruz–Catalina Ridge and Northern Channel Islands platform, California Continental Borderland, using submerged paleoshorelines",https://doi.org/10.1130/B26316.1,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""Eastern Northern Channel Islands Platform"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""al places. It is highly likely that sections of the shelf have failed and moved downslope, with material being deposited in the Santa Monica and Santa Cruz basins, modifying or destroying sections of the oldest lowstand terraces. In comparison, the slopes below the shelf break on the northern sides of the islands are gentler and display little evidence of gully formation or slope failure, possibly a result of the higher rate of deposition and greater volume of sediment being deposited in the Santa Barbara basin.""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 95.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": ""LGM"", ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-95,-95,-95,-95
