917af087bae70c82ef9e9b0f0c57bd7a5065c9f2de7b0f4bb09f07ae62516c92,sonnenburg2012,sea_level_indicator,3.2. Water levels,narrative_fallback_1,,,inferred_map,,-5.4,MSL,reported,submerged_beach,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-7.9, -2.9]",12.0,stratigraphic_context,"submerged beach at 3.2. Water levels, reported around 5.4 m depth",3.2. Water levels,"Holocene paleoshorelines, water levels and submerged prehistoric site potential of Rice Lake (Ontario, Canada)",https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jas.2012.05.035,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""3.2. Water levels"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""12 ka BP (Sonnenburg, 2010). The transgression of the wetland shoreline can be seen clearly in both the open lake and in the basin cores in the declining age of the peat deposits at higher elevations. In the open lake for example, the peat had an age of 9530 \u0003 50 bp (11,091e10,682 cal. BP) at 7.2 m bpl (RIL-11) and further up basin slope an ages of 9130 50 bp (10,478e10,204 cal. BP) at a depth of 5.4 m bpl (RIL-8) (Figs. 2 and 3). A similar trend was observed in the McIntyre lagoon, where the shoreline transgressed 1 m between 9470 50 bp (11,069e10,574 cal. BP) (RIL-10) and 8760 50 bp (10,114e9555 cal. BP) (RIL-16) (Fig. 2).""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 5.4, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""stratigraphic_context"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": 12.0, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-5.4,-5.4,-5.4,-5.4
