14dcb607d6addf2e03672680a30a265f551ecea02623d1a47f78b972fa36aac0,taylor1991,sea_level_indicator,taylor1991,heuristic_feature_1,2.033333333333333,-2.033333333333333,reported,100.0,-5068.0,MSL,SRTM15+V2,submerged_beach,heuristically extracted from explicit text,null,null,other,"MARINE TRANSGRESSION, SHORELINE EMERGENCE:",taylor1991,"MARINE TRANSGRESSION, SHORELINE EMERGENCE:",https://doi.org/10.1029/91JB00293,0.75,"Extracted using heuristic parser from pdf text after methods: mineru_hybrid_auto_markdown, mineru_content_list.","{""page"": ""1-2"", ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": null, ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""# MARINE TRANSGRESSION, SHORELINE EMERGENCE: # EVIDENCE IN SEABED AND TERRESTRIAL GROUND TEMPERATURES # OF CHANGING RELATIVE SEA LEVELS, ARCTIC CANADA Alan E. Taylor Terrain Sciences Division, Geological Survey of Canada, Ottawa, Ontario Abstract. Precise temperatures to depths of several hundred meters have been measured in abandoned petroleum exploration wells in coastal and offshore areas of the Canadian Arctic. In these regions, changes in relative sea level during the Quaternary have left a strong thermal signature on deep ground temperatures. Surface temperature changes of the order of 10-20 K accompanied shoreline emergence due to uplift in some regions and marine transgression due to eustatic changes in sea levels in others. Classical, analytic techniques are used to demonstrate th""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": null, ""reported_datum"": null, ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": -5068.0, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": -5068.0, ""derived_depth_m"": 5068.0, ""derivation_notes"": ""Elevation sampled from SRTM15+V2 at authoritative coordinates because source elevation was not reported.""}","[{""method"": ""other"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""No direct age model extracted from text.""}]",-5068,-5068,-5068,-5068
