363821d2ab77b8e16327a972f0260c009b06adb5d9b00475da1c8f88b056bf85,yanchilina2017,sea_level_indicator,5.1.3. Aeolian dunes and desert pans,narrative_fallback_1,,,inferred_map,,-55.0,MSL,reported,submerged_beach,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-57.5, -52.5]",null,other,"submerged beach at 5.1.3. Aeolian dunes and desert pans, reported around 55 m depth",5.1.3. Aeolian dunes and desert pans,"Compilation of geophysical, geochronological, and geochemical evidence indicates a rapid Mediterranean-derived submergence of the Black Sea's shelf and subsequent substantial salinification in the early Holocene",https://doi.org/10.1016/j.margeo.2016.11.001,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""5.1.3. Aeolian dunes and desert pans"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""of 0.70907 which is substantially more radiogenic than the composition of the Black Sea lake water at that time (0.70890). This discrepancy is ascribed to colonization of perched ponds at elevations high above the paleoshoreline of the Black Sea-Lake (Major et al., 2006). Scherbakov and Babak (1979) describe the same faunal assemblage in sediments from the Sea of Azov which they also interpret to be perched saline ponds during periods of lowered Black Sea level.""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 55.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""other"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": null, ""material"": null, ""notes"": ""Narrative fallback age context; review before analytical use.""}]",-55,-55,-55,-55
a265b7de40e6f638e5adc3811fb18295c6b16883d9f7312baf2e71358f66ebc2,yanchilina2017,sea_level_indicator,5.3. Lake was largely regressed immediately prior to its connection with the Mediterranean,narrative_fallback_2,,,inferred_map,,-55.0,MSL,reported,submerged_beach,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-57.5, -52.5]",null,other,"submerged beach at 5.3. Lake was largely regressed immediately prior to its connection with the Mediterranean, reported around 55 m depth",5.3. Lake was largely regressed immediately prior to its connection with the Mediterranean,"Compilation of geophysical, geochronological, and geochemical evidence indicates a rapid Mediterranean-derived submergence of the Black Sea's shelf and subsequent substantial salinification in the early Holocene",https://doi.org/10.1016/j.margeo.2016.11.001,0.55,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""5.3. Lake was largely regressed immediately prior to its connection with the Mediterranean"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""Such deposits that are found at elevations above the paleoshoreline on the middle and inner Black Sea-shelf and that also date to a period before the connection are anomalous. Very few records exist. On the Romanian Shelf, two Cardium edule specimens from BLKS98-14 at a depth of 55 mbsl are dated at 9580 \u00b1 80 and $9 5 8 0 \\pm 9 0 { } ^ { 1 4 } \\mathrm { C }$ years. The latter specimen has a $^ { 8 7 } \\mathrm { S r } / ^ { 8 6 } \\mathrm { S r }$ composition of $0 . 7 0 9 0 7 1$ , a measurement that shows that these mollusks did not inhabit an environment submerged by the Black Sea-Lake and instead, inhabited an environment disconn""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 55.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": nu