6490b5b9610a3ac885e6a2fd33029d9b7539819150a7d23aaf72e493c0dfe0e4,sager1992,sea_level_indicator,SL,narrative_fallback_1,8.6400349,-11.8400269,inferred_text,10000.0,-82.0,MSL,reported,submerged_beach,narrative fallback: submerged geomorphic sea-level feature,"[-84.5, -79.5]",null,other,"submerged beach at SL, reported around 82 m depth",Sierra Leone,Mississippi–Alabama Outer Continental Shelf Topographic Features Formed during the Late Pleistocene–Holocene Transgression,,0.8,Narrative fallback cluster from prose description of submerged palaeolandscape; depth uncertainty widened pending human review. Geocoded from contextual query 'SL'.,"{""page"": null, ""figure"": null, ""table"": null, ""section"": ""Discussion and Conclusions"", ""quote_or_paraphrase"": ""shallow side of the 74 to 82 m isobath band of RLM, and have consistent base depths averaging 73 m. Some have morphologies similar to barrier islands or longshore bars, which are typically sand bodies deposited near the shoreline and within a few meters of SL (Penland and others 1988). Indeed, the location of the ridges along the landward side of the 74 to 82 m feature band is just what would be expected had they formed contemporaneously, the ridges at the shoreline and the RLM in shallow water offshore. Though no samples were obtained from the ridges and we cannot be certain of their origin, the geophysical data show no tectonic or structural foundations for these features and thus the simplest hypothesis is that they are what they appear to be, lithified and submerged barrier islands or""}","{""reported_elevation_m"": null, ""reported_depth_m"": 82.0, ""reported_datum"": ""MSL"", ""reported_uncertainty_m"": null}","{""raw_raster_value_m"": null, ""applied_correction_m"": null, ""derived_elevation_m"": null, ""derived_depth_m"": null, ""derivation_notes"": ""Existing elevation preserved; no raster overwrite applied.""}","[{""method"": ""other"", ""relation"": ""unknown"", ""age_ka"": null, ""uncertainty_ka"": nu